name: Irena Akbar
tweet: 3) Nafs al-Mutma’in (The content soul): The soul which is content with Allah’s will. The only longing of this soul is to please Allah through doing good deeds. The soul is ‘mutma’in, that is, it is at peace or solace.

name: Irena Akbar
tweet: 2)Nafs al-Lawwaama (The reproaching soul): The soul that reproaches you or makes you feel guilty when you do something wrong. The person at this level of soul would err or commit sin but would regret it & repent & may even vow not to repeat it.

name: Irena Akbar
tweet: THREAD  The 3 levels of ‘nafs’ (soul/self) as per Islamic thought:  1) Nafs al-Ammaara (The ‘commanding soul): The soul that commands/dominates you to fulfill your desires, irrespective of whether they are sinful or not. You are dictated by desire with no concern for right/wrong

name: Irena Akbar
tweet: Absolutely incorrect. The root letters of ‘Marhoom’ and ‘Marham’ are different. The ‘h’ in ‘Marhoom’ (مرحوم) is ح whereas the ‘h’ in ‘marham’ (مرہم) is ہ Root letters are the base that give meanings to derived words.

name: Irena Akbar
tweet: Sometimes, the Urdu word ‘Maghfoor’ is added before the names of deceased persons. ‘Maghfoor’ is an Arabic-origin word which means ‘One who has been forgiven’. It comes from the root ‘ghafara’ which means ‘forgiveness’.   *The joy of learning*  #etymology #urdu #arabic

name: Irena Akbar
tweet: ‘Marhoom’ is an Arabic-origin word which means ‘someone who has received Allah’s Mercy’. ’Marhoom’ is derived from the root ‘raham’ which means ‘mercy’. More 👇🏼

name: Irena Akbar
tweet: THREAD  In Urdu, ‘Marhoom’ is added before names of deceased persons, like ‘Marhoom Riyaz Khan’. In terms of usage, ‘Marhoom’ is equivalent to the English ‘Late’ as the latter too is added before the names of deceased persons. But the meaning of ‘Marhoom’ is different. Read👇🏼

tweet: Khilaaf is an Urdu word for ‘against’ and is derived from Arabic. In Hindi, it is ‘virodh’. Noun of khilaaf is mukhaalifat. Khilaafat is a different word that means caliphate. As simple as that.

tweet: Dear Hindi channels, Don’t use Urdu word ‘khilaafat’ for ‘opposition’. The noun form of Urdu word ‘khilaaf’ (which means ‘against’) is ‘mukhaalifat’, NOT ‘khilaafat’. ‘Khilaafat’ is ‘caliphate’, comes from ‘khalifa’ (‘caliph’) Why not use Hindi ‘virodh’?
